    <string id="label_fruit">Fruit:</string>

    <string id="joyful_1_meditation">In silence, Mary gives her "Fiat." The Creator becomes a creature. Let us ask for the grace to surrender our lives completely to God. (Lk 1:38)</string>
    <string id="joyful_2_meditation">Bearing the Word, Mary hastens to Elizabeth. Let us carry Christ to others, not with many words, but through the joy of radiant charity. (Lk 1:39)</string>
    <string id="joyful_3_meditation">The King of the Universe is born in a stable. He becomes poor to enrich us. Let us detach our hearts from worldly goods to receive the true Treasure. (Lk 2:7)</string>
    <string id="joyful_4_meditation">Simeon recognizes the Light of nations. Let us offer ourselves to the Lord, to be purified and consecrated entirely to His service. (Lk 2:22)</string>
    <string id="joyful_5_meditation">Jesus teaches the absolute primacy of the Father. May the loss of His presence be unbearable to us; let us seek Him always in the temple of our heart. (Lk 2:49)</string>

    <string id="sorrowful_1_meditation">Facing sin, Jesus sweats blood. "Not my will, but Yours." Let us unite our anxieties with His perfect offering and say "Yes" to God. (Lk 22:42)</string>
    <string id="sorrowful_2_meditation">The innocent Lamb is scourged to atone for sins of the flesh. Let us not indulge our bodies, but unite our sufferings to His holy wounds. (Is 53:5)</string>
    <string id="sorrowful_3_meditation">The King of Kings is crowned with mockery. He atones for our pride. Let us accept humiliations with humility, that He may reign in our minds. (Mt 27:29)</string>
    <string id="sorrowful_4_meditation">Jesus embraces the Cross of our salvation. Let us not refuse our daily crosses; carried with Him, they become the key that opens Heaven. (Lk 23:26)</string>
    <string id="sorrowful_5_meditation">From the Cross, He gives us everything: His forgiveness and His Mother. Let us live no longer for ourselves, but for Him who died for us. (Jn 19:26)</string>

    <string id="glorious_1_meditation">The tomb is empty, death is conquered. Let Easter light dispel our darkness: if we die with Him, we shall live with Him forever. (Mt 28:6)</string>
    <string id="glorious_2_meditation">Jesus returns to the Father to prepare a place for us. Let us lift up our hearts: our true homeland is in Heaven, not on this earth. (Acts 1:9)</string>
    <string id="glorious_3_meditation">The Fire of the Spirit descends. It turns fear into boldness. Come Holy Spirit, kindle in us Your charity and make us burning witnesses. (Acts 2:4)</string>
    <string id="glorious_4_meditation">The Mother of God is assumed into glory. She is the image of what we shall be. Let us ask her to assist us at the hour of our death. (Tradition)</string>
    <string id="glorious_5_meditation">Mary is Queen and Mediatrix of all graces. Let us trust in her maternal protection: she will lead us safely to the throne of her Son. (Rev 12:1)</string>

    <string id="luminous_1_meditation">The Innocent One descends into the waters. Let us awaken the grace of our Baptism: we are children of God, called to listen to Jesus. (Mt 3:17)</string>
    <string id="luminous_2_meditation">At Mary's prayer, Jesus changes water into wine. Trusting in her intercession ("Do whatever He tells you"), let us entrust our needs to Christ. (Jn 2:5)</string>
    <string id="luminous_3_meditation">The Kingdom is here. Let us welcome His Word of truth that sets us free, renouncing sin to live according to the Beatitudes. (Mk 1:15)</string>
    <string id="luminous_4_meditation">The glory of God shines through Christ's humanity. Let us fix our gaze on His luminous Face to endure the trials of faith with hope. (Mt 17:2)</string>
    <string id="luminous_5_meditation">"This is my body given for you." Jesus becomes food to remain in us. Let us draw strength from the Eucharist to love as He loved. (Lk 22:19)</string>

